  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Comprehensive Action Plan (CAP) for Afghanistan and Neighboring Countries</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In 2021 more than 1,260,000 undocumented Afghans returned from Pakistan and the Islamic Republic of Iran &#x2014; the highest return total of any year on record. So far in 2022, almost 280,000 individuals have returned from Islamic Republic of Iran and Pakistan, figures increasing by 62 per cent across the first three months alone. At the same time, the humanitarian situation in Afghanistan has further deteriorated with significant consequences for the most vulnerable among the population. Already an estimated 72% of Afghans are living below the poverty line, and it is predicted that 97% of the population could fall into poverty by the end of 2022 unless the political and economic crises are urgently addressed. In Afghanistan, IOM continues to deliver lifesaving post-arrival assistance to the most vulnerable undocumented returnees from the Islamic Republic of Islamic Republic of Iran and Pakistan. In Pakistan, IOM focuses on contributing towards strengthening the access of vulnerable Afghans and host community households to multi-sectoral humanitarian assistance, with a focus on community-based protection and cash-based assistance to highly vulnerable households within targeted communities.</narrative>
  </description>
